break acts as continue (advances to next iteration)
for iterates in reverse - visits 1, 2, 3 in order
break before input x - every iteration skips printing, so nothing printed
// for x in [3, 2, 1] }
// break
// input x
// {
// input ~"after-break-loop"
continue acts as break (exits the loop)
for loop visits 1 first; continue exits immediately
// for y in [3, 2, 1] }
// input y
// continue
// {
// input ~"after-continue-loop"
